==Translingual==

===Symbol===
'''α'''
# The [[lower case]] letter [[alpha]], the first letter of the modern [[w:Greek alphabet|Greek alphabet]].
# The [[fine structure constant]].
# Used in [[chemical]] [[nomenclature]].
# Used to identify the brightest [[star]] in a [[constellation]] (eg β-Orion or Rigel in [[Orion]]).
# Used in marking scheme: α, β, γ or α+, α, α-, β etc.
:'''Examples'''
:# [[alpha particle|α-particle]].
:# [[α-naphthol]]
:# [[w:Alpha Centauri|α-Centauri]]


'''α''''
# The number one in [[w:Greek numerals|Greek numerals]].

''',α'''
# The number 1000 in Greek numerals.

===Etymology===
* Derived from the Phoenician letter [[w:Aleph (letter)|Aleph]] [[Image:phoenician_aleph.png|20px|Aleph]].

===Pronunciation===
# In modern Greek it represents the [[w:Open front unrounded vowel|[a]]] sound similar to the '''a''' in ''hat'' and ''Athens'' (in Greek ''η Αθήνα'').
# [[IPA]] /a/
# [[SAMPA]] /a/

In modern Greek it represents the [a] sound similar to the a in hat

